05682nam a22008775i 9780674419582DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)900717587  a97806744195827 a10.4159/harvard.97806744195822doi  a(DE-B1597)427261  a(OCoLC)880147755  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHD3850 7aBUS0790002bisacsh04a338.6/21 aMusacchio, Aldo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReinventing State Capitalism :bLeviathan in Business, Brazil and Beyond /cAldo Musacchio. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (357 p.) :b2 line illustrations, 31 graphs, 42 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. The Reinvention of State Capitalism around the World -- t2. The Rise and Fall of Leviathan as an Entrepreneur -- t3. Views on State Capitalism -- tPart II. Leviathan as an Entrepreneur and Majority Investor -- t4. The Evolution of State Capitalism in Brazil -- t5. Leviathan as a Manager: Do CEOs of SOEs Matter? -- t6. The Fall of Leviathan as an Entrepreneur in Brazil -- t7. Taming Leviathan? Corporate Governance in National Oil Companies -- tPart III Leviathan as a Minority Investor -- t8. Leviathan as a Minority Shareholder -- t9. Leviathan’s Temptation: The Case of Vale -- t10. Leviathan as a Lender: Development Banks and State Capitalism -- t11. Leviathan as a Lender: Industrial Policy versus Politics -- t12. Conclusions and Lessons -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe wave of liberalization that swept world markets in the 1980s and 90s altered the ways that governments manage their economies. Reinventing State Capitalism analyzes the rise of new species of state capitalism in which governments interact with private investors either as majority or minority shareholders in publicly-traded corporations or as financial backers of purely private firms (the so-called "national champions"). Focusing on a detailed quantitative assessment of Brazil's economic performance from 1976 to 2009, Aldo Musacchio and Sergio Lazzarini examine how these models of state capitalism influence corporate investment and performance. According to one model, the state acts as a majority investor, granting the state-owned enterprise (SOE) financial autonomy and allowing professional management. This form, the authors argue, has reduced many agency problems commonly faced by state ownership. According to another hybrid model, the state uses sovereign wealth funds, holding companies, and development banks to acquire a small share of equity ownership in a corporation, thereby potentially alleviating capital constraints and leveraging latent capabilities. Both models have benefits and costs. Yet neither model has entirely eliminated the temptation of governments to intervene in the operation of natural resource industries and other large strategic enterprises. Nevertheless, the longstanding debate over whether private ownership is superior or inferior to state capitalism has become irrelevant, Musacchio and Lazzarini conclude. Private ownership is now mingled with state capital on a global scale.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBeteiligung. 0aCapitalismxBrazil. 0aCapitalism. 0aGovernment ownershipxBrazil. 0aGovernment ownershipzBrazil. 0aGovernment ownership. 0aKapitalismus. 0aStaat. 0aStaatskapitalismus. 0aStaatsunternehmen. 0aWirtschaft. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Government & Business.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DG